\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{Y}(y) & =\int_{0}^{1}f_{Y|X=x}(y)f_{X}(x)dx=\int_{0}^{1}\binom{n}{y}\theta^{y}(1-\theta)^{n-y}3\cdot(1-\theta)^{2}d\theta\\
 & =3\binom{n}{y}\int_{0}^{1}\theta^{y}(1-\theta)^{n-y+2}d\theta
\end{align*}

\end_inset

this integral is easy to solve by realizing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{y}(1-\theta)^{n-y+2}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the 
\begin_inset Formula $Beta(y+1,n-y+3)$
\end_inset

 density, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\theta^{y}(1-\theta)^{n-y+2}d\theta=\frac{\Gamma(y+1)\Gamma(n-y+3)}{\Gamma(n+4)}.
\]

\end_inset

This is enough for full points, but the distribution can be simplified further
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
