First note that the density of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim\Gamma(\alpha,1)$
\end_inset

 is of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{X}(x)=\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)}x^{\alpha-1}e^{-x}
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U=X+Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V=X/(X+Y)$
\end_inset

.
 The inverse transformation is 
\begin_inset Formula $X=UV$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=U-UV=U(1-V)$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=\left|\begin{array}{cc}
v & u\\
1-v & -u
\end{array}\right|=-vu-u(1-v)=-u
\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|J\right|=u$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{U,V}(u,v) & =f_{X}(uv)f_{Y}(u(1-v))\cdot\left|J\right|=\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)}(uv)^{\alpha-1}e^{-uv}\frac{1}{\Gamma(\beta)}(u(1-v))^{\beta-1}e^{-u(1-v)}\cdot u\\
 & =\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)\Gamma(\beta)}u^{\alpha}u^{\beta-1}e^{-u}v{}^{\alpha-1}(1-v){}^{\beta-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U,V}(u,v)$
\end_inset

 can be factorized as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U,V}(u,v)=g(u)h(v)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 are independent.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
